"Change of admission" is the key variable in this dataset. With this dataset, we will be able to tell which resume/application variables will impact one's chance to be admitted into this University.

Most measures of accomplishment are highly correlated with one another and all lead to a higher calculation for 'Change of admission'. Interestingly, having research experience seems to be the weakest determinant of other measures of academic achievement and has the lowest impact on one's chances.

Importantly, the histograms in the pairplot above reveal that the observations take on roughly normal distributions so scaling will not be necessary.

Furthermore, the relationships of all individual variables seem to be linearly correlated, so a linear regression is likely the best model.

def print_margin(rmse):
    print(f'{round(rmse * 100, 1)}% from the actual score')
    print(f'{round(rmse / (0.97 - 0.34) * 100, 1)}% within the observed range')
    
print('training set')
print_margin(train_rmse)
print('\n')
print('testing set')
print_margin(test_rmse)

training set
6.2% from the actual score
9.9% within the observed range


testing set
6.8% from the actual score
10.8% within the observed range

I didn't see a need to stratify, scale, or encode any features, so the preprocessing was all related to the test split and linear regression process. The RMSE of the training set was 0.063. This is only 6.3% of the total range (0.0 to 1.0 scale) and 10% of the observed range (0.34 to 0.97).

In my view, this is a pretty good prediction given the subjective nature of admissions selection in general.

Furthermore, the training set corroborated this model with an RMSE of 0.066. This is only 6.6% of the total range and 10.5% of the observed range. Still a great model.

# Authors: Mathew Kallada & Chris Teplovs
# License: BSD 3 clause
"""
=========================================
Plot Hierarachical Clustering Dendrogram 
=========================================
This example plots the corresponding dendrogram of a hierarchical clustering
using AgglomerativeClustering and the dendrogram method available in scipy.
"""

import numpy as np

from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import dendrogram
from sklearn.cluster import AgglomerativeClustering

def plot_dendrogram(pipeline, **kwargs):

    # Children of hierarchical clustering
    children = pipeline.named_steps.cluster.children_

    # Distances between each pair of children
    # Since we don't have this information, we can use a uniform one for plotting
    distance = np.arange(children.shape[0])

    # The number of observations contained in each cluster level
    no_of_observations = np.arange(2, children.shape[0]+2)

    # Create linkage matrix and then plot the dendrogram
    linkage_matrix = np.column_stack([children, distance, no_of_observations]).astype(float)


    # Plot the corresponding dendrogram
    dendrogram(linkage_matrix, **kwargs)
    
    threshold = kwargs.pop('color_threshold')
    plt.axhline(threshold,color='red')

I added the 'admitted' column values to the labels for each observation. This gave me a sense of how the admitted status determined by my threshold arranged themselves into groups. After playing with the threshold value a bit, I was delighted to find that with a cut line of 38, there were only 2 groups and all admitted students fell into 1 group. There were no admissions in the other group.

To some degree, this is a self-fulfilling prophecy since I changed my threshold to yield grouped results, but 0.8 was actually my first choice which I only modified later to align with my expectation of a 20% admission rate.

Use the average silhouette score to determine the optimal number of clusters and show the silhouette plot for the optimal number of clusters.

In [31]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_samples, silhouette_score

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.cm as cm # colormaps
import numpy as np

def plot_silhouettes(features, pipeline, cluster_list=[2, 3, 4, 5, 6]):
    for n_clusters in cluster_list:
        # Create a subplot with 1 row and 2 columns
        fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2)
        fig.set_size_inches(18, 7)

        # The 1st subplot is the silhouette plot
        # The silhouette coefficient can range from -1, 1 but in this example all
        # lie within [-0.1, 1]
        ax1.set_xlim([-0.1, 1])
        # The (n_clusters+1)*10 is for inserting blank space between silhouette
        # plots of individual clusters, to demarcate them clearly.
        ax1.set_ylim([0, len(features) + (n_clusters + 1) * 10])

        # Initialize the clusterer with n_clusters value and a random generator
        # seed of 42 for reproducibility.
        
        pipeline.named_steps.cluster.set_params(n_clusters=n_clusters)
        clusterer = pipeline.named_steps.cluster
        cluster_labels = clusterer.fit_predict(features)

        # The silhouette_score gives the average value for all the samples.
        # This gives a perspective into the density and separation of the formed
        # clusters
        silhouette_avg = silhouette_score(features, cluster_labels)
        print("For n_clusters =", n_clusters,
              "The average silhouette_score is :", silhouette_avg)

        # Compute the silhouette scores for each sample
        sample_silhouette_values = silhouette_samples(features, cluster_labels)

        y_lower = 10
        for i in range(n_clusters):
            # Aggregate the silhouette scores for samples belonging to
            # cluster i, and sort them
            ith_cluster_silhouette_values = sample_silhouette_values[cluster_labels == i]

            ith_cluster_silhouette_values.sort()

            size_cluster_i = ith_cluster_silhouette_values.shape[0]
            y_upper = y_lower + size_cluster_i

            color = cm.nipy_spectral(float(i) / n_clusters)
            ax1.fill_betweenx(np.arange(y_lower, y_upper),
                              0, ith_cluster_silhouette_values,
                              facecolor=color, edgecolor=color, alpha=0.7)

            # Label the silhouette plots with their cluster numbers at the middle
            ax1.text(-0.05, y_lower + 0.5 * size_cluster_i, str(i))

            # Compute the new y_lower for next plot
            y_lower = y_upper + 10  # 10 for the 0 samples

        ax1.set_title("The silhouette plot for the various clusters.")
        ax1.set_xlabel("The silhouette coefficient values")
        ax1.set_ylabel("Cluster label")

        # The vertical line for average silhouette score of all the values
        ax1.axvline(x=silhouette_avg, color="red", linestyle="--")

        ax1.set_yticks([])  # Clear the yaxis labels / ticks
        ax1.set_xticks([-0.1, 0, 0.2, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8, 1])

        # 2nd Plot showing the actual clusters formed
        colors = cm.nipy_spectral(cluster_labels.astype(float) / n_clusters)
        ax2.scatter(features.values[:, 0], features.values[:, 1], marker='.', s=30, lw=0, alpha=0.7,
                    c=colors, edgecolor='k') #here 4

        # Labeling the clusters
        centers = clusterer.cluster_centers_
        # Draw white circles at cluster centers
        ax2.scatter(centers[:, 0], centers[:, 1], marker='o',
                    c="white", alpha=1, s=200, edgecolor='k')

        for i, c in enumerate(centers):
            ax2.scatter(c[0], c[1], marker='$%d$' % i, alpha=1,
                        s=50, edgecolor='k')

        ax2.set_title("The visualization of the clustered data.")
        ax2.set_xlabel("Feature space for the 1st feature")
        ax2.set_ylabel("Feature space for the 2nd feature")

        plt.suptitle(("Silhouette analysis for KMeans clustering on sample data "
                      "with n_clusters = %d" % n_clusters),
                     fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')

    plt.show()

Although there is some overlap between the groupings of admitted and non-admitted students, there is still a clear relationship. The lower the value along either axis, the higher the probability of admittance.

I experimented with perplexities between 5 and 60 and interactions between 1000 and 3000. Ultimately the number of iterations did not affect the output very much. Perplexity between 30 and 50 grouped the observations by 'admitted' very well, however, I chose 50 because of the tightness of the observations and color groups.
